ew Summary Pregnancy Summary Pregnancy History Diagnoses Disease Category Disease Condition Prescriptions Medical Supplies Normal Moderate Malnutrition Severe Malnutrition %1$s (%2$s) Severe Dehydration Pneumonia BPM Malaria %1$d (≥ %2$d days) HH ID Date of Onset Date of Review Different Login! There is some unsynchronized data associated with the last user (%1$s). Kindly sync data. Sync Status Something went wrong during upload. Please try again later %1$d record yet to sync Instructions Measuring MUAC Checking for Oedema Chest in-drawing Patient On Treatment Treatment for Pneumonia Amoxicillin 250mg tab No Referral / No Treatment Required Select Ask the mother to remove any clothing that covers the child’s left arm. Identify the midpoint of the child’s left upper arm. This can be done by taking a piece of string (or the tape itself), place one end on the tip of the child’s shoulder and the other on the elbow Now bend the string up in a loop to double it so the point at the elbow is placed together with the point on the shoulder with a loop hanging down – the end of the straightened loop indicates the midpoint. Straighten the child’s arm and wrap the tape around the arm at the midpoint. Make sure the tape is flat around the skin. Inspect the tension of the tape on the child’s arm. Make sure the tape has the proper tension and is not too tight so that the skin is compressed or too loose so that the tape does not contact the skin all the way round the arm. When the tape is in the correct position on the arm with correct tension, pay attention to the color of MUAC Use your thumbs to press gently on the top of both feet at the same time and say “1001 1002 and 1003”. Lift the fingers and observe if a ‘pit’ remains The child has oedema if a pit remains in both feet when you lift your thumbs The child has chest in-drawing if the lower chest wall goes IN when the child breathes IN. Chest in-drawing is not visible when the child breathes out. For chest in-drawing to be present, it must be clearly visible and present at every breath. 34 weeks(Premature) Gestational Age 1780gms weeks(Low birth weight) "Last Menstrual Period " Estimated Delivery Date Refer Patient Treatment Next visit date reload Select Date Selected Referral Date Referral Reason Referred To Referred By Date of Delivery Delivery Type Labour/Delivery Date of Delivery Date of Labour Onset Delivery Type Delivery At No of Neonates Time of Delivery Time of Labour Onset Delivery By Delivery By (Others) Delivery Status Please enter valid input Select Date Number Hour Minutes Member registration \n completed successfully. Member successfully linked to \n this household Patient ID: %1$s Result - Mother Result - Neonate ANC Visit PNC Visit If you leave this screen, your entered data will not be saved. Add New Member Birth History Breathing problems at birth Clinical Summary & Vital Signs Weight (in kg) WAZ Temperature (in °C) Temperature Respiration Rate Rate minute Height (in cm) WHZ Immunisation Status Repeat (if >60) Breast Feeding Exclusive Breast Feeding Vitamin A for mother Mother Signs/Symptoms observed General Condition of Mother Risk Factors State of the Perineum Episiotomy Tear TT Dose taken so far Status Neonate Neonate Outcome Male Female State of Baby Abnormal Birth Weight Signs/Symptoms observed State of the Baby APGAR Score 1 Deg 2 Deg 3 Deg 4 Deg Labour/Delivery Medical Review Labour/Delivery Search medication and add Search lab/radiology test and add Medication Name Frequency Prescribed Days Quantity No. of fetus Pregnancy Details Gravida Height Weight (in kg) Weight BMI : Systolic(mmHg) Diastolic(mmHg) + Parity "Please enter weight between 10 to 400" "Please enter weight between 0.1 to 400" "Please enter height between 10 to 300" "Please enter height between 50 to 300" "Please enter Gestational age below 60" Patient Blood Group Diastolic pressure should be above 30 Pulse should be above 35 Systolic pressure should be above 30 Examination Clinician Name The review